<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1072,2043]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,1072,1098]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Comparisons.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[372,603,1072,1098]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[372,603,1072,1098]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Sceloporus hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the smallest species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1011,1128,1072,1098]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scalaris">
<emphasis box="[1011,1128,1072,1098]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. scalaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, having a mean SVL of 
<quantity box="[182,285,1108,1135]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.54" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="45.4">45.4 mm</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liner &amp; Dixon" authorityYear="1992" box="[296,515,1108,1134]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chaneyi">
<emphasis box="[296,515,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Sceloporus chaneyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, previously reported to be the smallest 
<taxonomicName box="[959,1077,1108,1134]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scalaris">
<emphasis box="[959,1077,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. scalaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group species, has a mean SVL of 
<quantity box="[182,283,1144,1171]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.57" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="45.7">45.7 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Liner, E. A. &amp; Dixon, J. R." box="[298,536,1144,1170]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="421 - 427" refId="ref12975" refString="Liner, E. A. &amp; Dixon, J. R. (1992) A new species of the Sceloporus scalaris group from Cerro Pena Nevada, Nuevo Leon, Mexico (Sauria: Iguanidae). The Texas Journal of Science, 44, 421 - 427." type="journal article" year="1992">Liner &amp; Dixon 1992</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[556,788,1144,1170]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[556,788,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Sceloporus hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1000,1126,1144,1170]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subniger">
<emphasis box="[1000,1126,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. subniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[1183,1281,1144,1170]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dixoni">
<emphasis box="[1183,1281,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. dixoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing with them a single canthal on each side of the head, relatively short legs (tibia length/head length proportion less than 0.9), small adult size (maximum SVL less than 
<quantity box="[685,768,1216,1243]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="63.0">63 mm</quantity>
), 36–50 dorsal scales, extensive dark pigment on the venter of adult males, a black-barred or darkly mottled chin/throat in adult males, orange or rust-colored flanks in adult males, and oviparity. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[393,625,1288,1314]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[393,625,1288,1314]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Sceloporus hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[931,1057,1288,1314]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subniger">
<emphasis box="[931,1057,1288,1314]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. subniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of its smaller adult size (maximum SVL = 
<quantity box="[472,550,1323,1349]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="47.0">47 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[584,711,1323,1349]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[584,711,1323,1349]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<quantity box="[754,833,1323,1349]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="62.0">62 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName box="[866,991,1323,1349]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subniger">
<emphasis box="[866,991,1323,1349]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. subniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; average SVL = 
<quantity box="[1178,1277,1323,1350]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.54" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="45.4">45.4 mm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity box="[1321,1424,1323,1349]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.86" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="48.6">48.6 mm</quantity>
), more dorsal scales (average of 43 vs. 41), more scales around midbody (average of 43 vs. 41), more ventral scales (average of 38 vs. 34), and fewer scales bordering the interpariatel scale (average of 14 vs. 16). Female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[1309,1437,1392,1418]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[1309,1437,1392,1418]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also have considerably less mottling on the ventral surface than female 
<taxonomicName box="[976,1105,1427,1453]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subniger">
<emphasis box="[976,1105,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. subniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[1121,1355,1427,1453]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[1121,1355,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Sceloporus hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[212,310,1461,1488]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dixoni">
<emphasis box="[212,310,1461,1488]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. dixoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of their smaller adult size (maximum SVL = 
<quantity box="[1042,1121,1462,1488]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="47.0">47 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[1156,1284,1461,1488]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[1156,1284,1461,1488]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<quantity box="[1329,1408,1461,1488]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="54.0">54 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,250,1496,1522]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dixoni">
<emphasis box="[151,250,1496,1522]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. dixoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; average SVL = 
<quantity box="[442,542,1496,1523]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.54" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="45.4">45.4 mm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity box="[589,693,1496,1523]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.71" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="mm" value="47.1">47.1 mm</quantity>
), slightly shorter legs (average tibia length/head length proportion 0.84 vs. 0.86), more ventral scales (average = 38 vs. 35), more dorsal scales (41–47, average = 43 vs. 37–45, average = 41), and more scales around midbody (40–45, average = 43 vs. 37–43, average = 40).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="350" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1072,2043]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1600,1626]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Greek word 
<emphasis box="[936,1041,1600,1626]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">hesperos,</emphasis>
meaning “western”, and is used in reference to the 
<typeStatus box="[332,380,1635,1661]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">type</typeStatus>
locality located at the far western end of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="351" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1072,2043]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1436,151,247]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="351" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1669,1695]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Distribution.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, H. M." box="[359,565,1669,1696]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="1 - 427" refId="ref13607" refString="Smith, H. M. (1939) The Mexican and Central American lizards of the genus Sceloporus. Zoological Series: Field Museum of Natural History, 26, 1 - 427." type="journal article" year="1939">Smith (1939: 356)</bibRefCitation>
cites several published records from the late 1800s for 
<taxonomicName authority="aeneus" box="[1184,1375,1670,1696]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="aeneus" subSpecies="aeneus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1375,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. aeneus aeneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[151,232,1704,1730]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
: “N of Rio Santiago (
<bibRefCitation author="Gunther, A. C. L. G." box="[469,630,1704,1730]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" refId="ref12459" refString="Gunther, A. C. L. G. (1890) Biologia Centrali-Americana. Reptilia and Batrachia. Porter, London." type="book" year="1890">Günther 1890</bibRefCitation>
); La Cumbre de los Arrastrados (
<bibRefCitation author="Boulenger, G. A." box="[997,1182,1704,1730]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="474 - 522" refId="ref11145" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1897) A revision of the lizards of the genus Sceloporus. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1897, 474 - 522." type="journal article" year="1897">Boulenger 1897</bibRefCitation>
); Hda. Santa Gertrudis (
<bibRefCitation author="Boulenger, G. A." box="[159,346,1739,1765]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="474 - 522" refId="ref11145" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1897) A revision of the lizards of the genus Sceloporus. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1897, 474 - 522." type="journal article" year="1897">Boulenger 1897</bibRefCitation>
).” Over 50 years later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, H. M. &amp; Camarillo-Rangel, J. L. &amp; Chiszar, D." box="[603,871,1739,1765]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="130 - 139" refId="ref13642" refString="Smith, H. M., Camarillo-Rangel, J. L. &amp; Chiszar, D. (1993) The status of the members of the Sceloporus aeneus complex (Reptilia: Sauria) of Mexico. Bulletin of the Maryland Herpetological Society, 29, 130 - 139." type="journal article" year="1993">
Smith 
<emphasis box="[677,726,1739,1765]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">et al</emphasis>
. (1993: 133)
</bibRefCitation>
commented that Boulenger’s records from 
<collectingRegion box="[1360,1436,1739,1765]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
“appear to be too far west to be accepted without verification.” If Boulenger’s records are indeed correct, specimens from La Cumbre de los Arrastrados and Hacienda Santa Gertrudis in the Sierra de Cuale might be referable to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A narrow ridge above 
<quantity box="[513,605,1843,1869]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="2200.0">2,200 m</quantity>
extends across southwestern 
<collectingRegion box="[935,1011,1843,1869]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
from the 
<typeStatus box="[1121,1169,1843,1869]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Sierra de Mascota through the Sierra de Cuale to the Sierra de Manantlán. The reptiles and amphibians in this remote region of 
<collectingCountry box="[183,269,1912,1938]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Mexico</collectingCountry>
remain poorly sampled (
<bibRefCitation author="Reyes-Velasco, J. &amp; Grunwald, C. I. &amp; Jones, J. M. &amp; Weatherman, G. N." box="[556,859,1912,1939]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" pagination="19 - 25" refId="ref13405" refString="Reyes-Velasco, J., Grunwald, C. I., Jones, J. M. &amp; Weatherman, G. N. (2010) Rediscovery of the rare Autlan longtailed rattlesnake, Crotalus lannomi. Herpetological Review, 41, 19 - 25." type="journal article" year="2010">
Reyes-Velasco 
<emphasis box="[731,782,1912,1938]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
). If suitable montane bunchgrass habitat is present along the forested mountain pass connecting these three sierras, then it is conceivable that additional populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,279,1981,2008]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[151,279,1981,2008]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will be found here. For now, the only known population of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[948,1076,1981,2008]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[948,1076,1981,2008]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is from the high-elevation pineoak forest at the 
<typeStatus box="[334,382,2017,2043]" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Sierra de Mascota of 
<collectingRegion box="[782,862,2016,2042]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="15" pageNumber="350">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
. The low-elevation valleys trending northwest from the Nevado de 
<collectingRegion box="[320,402,151,177]" country="Mexico" name="Colima" pageId="16" pageNumber="351">Colima</collectingRegion>
likely serve as a geographic barrier between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[910,1038,151,177]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="351" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[910,1038,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="351">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryson &amp; Grummer &amp; Connors &amp; Tirpak &amp; Mccormack &amp; Klicka" authorityYear="2021" box="[1093,1191,151,177]" class="Reptilia" family="Phrynosomatidae" genus="Sceloporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="351" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dixoni">
<emphasis box="[1093,1191,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="351">S. dixoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This lower-elevation area is also inhabited by 
